{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b3a89581-1939-4a9d-b431-ae0fe8b88c7f","content":"The repository is empty, so I'll answer from general knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, if your NativeAOT app crashes and `createdump` isn't available (it's not bundled with NativeAOT builds), you can recover a crash dump via these steps:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** — by default macOS disables them. Before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n\n3. **Disable SIP restrictions (if needed)** — on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection can block core dumps for certain processes. You may need to sign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement:\n   ```bash\n   codesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist ./myapp\n   ```\n   where `entitlements.plist` contains:\n   ```xml\n   <key>com.apple.security.get-task-allow</key>\n   <true/>\n   ```\n\n4. **Reproduce the crash** — run the app; the core file appears at the path you configured.\n\n5. **Analyze with lldb**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./myapp -c /tmp/cores/core.<PID>\n   bt        # backtrace\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternative: attach lldb before the crash**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./myapp\n   run\n   # after crash, use `bt`, `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n   ```\n\nThe Apple-generated `.ips` report (step 1) is often the quickest path — it includes the stack trace and faulting thread without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"933f86ee-9d47-4d89-b420-8a272828b3db","outputTokens":475,"requestId":"4193:11463F:62FEF18:6C3D545:69F163CE"},"id":"9a786895-6270-4bc0-b29b-8c65fe6d443e","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:50:21.549Z","parentId":"c6ebf5a0-292b-4d0d-8b26-e037a6a73e89"}
